{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 18:40:07.252840", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nSummary of Network Health\\n- Layer-3 connectivity across the enterprise appears normal. Cross-subnet reachability is healthy with 0% packet loss and low, stable RTTs between hosts and servers (including to 10.200.0.2, the DNS server).\\n- HTTP services are reachable by IP. Direct curls to web servers and the load balancer’s IP (10.200.0.7) succeed with normal connect/TTFB timings.\\n- Name resolution is failing end-to-end. Hostname-based HTTP requests (e.g., http://web99.local, http://web0.local) consistently time out, even though the same services are reachable by IP.\\n\\nObserved Anomalies\\n- DNS lookups fail from client hosts:\\n  - curl to hostnames (web99.local, web0.local) shows ~5.0s totals with zeroed timing stages, consistent with DNS resolution timeout.\\n  - nslookup and dig from hosts to 10.200.0.2 time out.\\n- DNS lookups fail on the DNS server itself:\\n  - dig @127.0.0.1 web99.local, dig @10.200.0.2 web99.local, and even dig SOA for the local zone all time out on dns_server.\\n- Despite failures, the DNS daemon appears to be up and listening:\\n  - named service is active (running).\\n  - Listening sockets for UDP/TCP 53 exist on 10.200.0.2 and 127.0.0.1.\\n  - The zone is configured: /etc/bind/named.conf includes zone \"local\" with db.local containing A records for ns1, web0–web3, and web99, and named-checkconf -z shows “zone local/IN: loaded …”.\\n  - /etc/resolv.conf on clients points to 10.200.0.2 and nsswitch.conf uses “hosts: files dns”, so clients are correctly configured to use this DNS.\\n\\nFault Localization\\n- The fault is localized to the DNS server (dns_server at 10.200.0.2).\\n\\nRoot Cause Analysis\\n- A local firewall on the DNS server is blocking DNS traffic:\\n  - nftables rules show an inet filter table with explicit drops for both tcp dport 53 and udp dport 53 in the input, forward, and output chains:\\n    - chain input: tcp dport 53 drop; udp dport 53 drop\\n    - chain forward: tcp dport 53 drop; udp dport 53 drop\\n    - chain output: tcp dport 53 drop; udp dport 53 drop\\n  - These rules prevent the DNS server from receiving queries (input), sending responses (output), and forwarding DNS if relevant. This explains why both remote clients and the server itself (loopback and self-queries) experience timeouts.\\n- Routing and service availability are otherwise healthy:\\n  - OSPF/L3 pathing is intact (pings across areas/subnets are good).\\n  - HTTP services via IP are reachable and responsive (load balancer and web servers).\\n  - DHCP and host addressing appear correct (clients have addresses in expected subnets; resolv.conf points to the correct DNS IP).\\n\\nImpact\\n- All hostname-based access to services in the local zone (e.g., web0.local … web3.local, web99.local) fails due to DNS queries being dropped at the DNS server.\\n- Services are only accessible by IP, which degrades user experience and breaks workflows relying on FQDNs.\\n\\nEvidence Highlights\\n- curl_web_test to hostnames from multiple hosts: repeated ~5s timeouts; to IPs: normal timings.\\n- dig/nslookup timeouts from both clients and the DNS server itself.\\n- named active and listening on 10.200.0.2:53 and 127.0.0.1:53.\\n- nft list ruleset showing explicit drops for DNS ports in all chains.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- Anomaly detected: DNS resolution outage.\\n- Faulty device: dns_server (10.200.0.2).\\n- Root cause: Misconfigured nftables firewall rules on dns_server dropping both inbound and outbound DNS (TCP/UDP 53), causing all DNS queries to time out despite the authoritative zone being correctly configured and named running., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='cb8f4346-3651-4e32-ad8f-10019669cad9'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
